brightness colours widely unlike and different *be one another. More- over the unlike figures do not in the least hinder' or prevent the whole figure from being a square on the outside3 but the various colours of things are a let and hindrance to the whole things being of a uniform, brightness.

Then too the reason which leads and draws us on sometimes to assign colours to the first-beginnings of things, falls to the ground, since* white things are not produced from white, nor those which are black from black, but out of things of various colours. For white things will much more readily rise up and be born from no colour than from a white or any other colour which thwarts and opposes it.

Moreover since colours cannot exist without light and first-begin- nings of things do not come out into the light, you may be sure they are clothed with no colour. For what colour can there be in total darkness? nay it changes in the light itself according as its brightness comes from a straight or slanting stroke of light.
